    11	This is the right place to start, but the chain understates how asymmetric the candidate spaces are.
    12	
    13	- `L^3` is not just one more critical space on a list. It already sits next to very strong endpoint regularity results, so any minimal-element program there has to explain why those results do not already collapse the route or why the hypothetical critical element evades them only in a very specific way.
    14	- `\dot H^{1/2}` has a cleaner Hilbert-space profile technology than `BMO^{-1}`, but it is less naturally tied to the suitable-weak-solution machinery that usually feeds local energy and backward-uniqueness style arguments.
    15	- `BMO^{-1}` is the weakest candidate in this menu for a compactness-rigidity program. It is excellent for small-data mild theory, but it is a poor default host for a large-data minimal blowup extraction unless one can point to a concrete nonlinear profile decomposition and a robust stability theory in exactly that setting.
    16	
    17	So the step's framing is too loose. "Rank realistic spaces" sounds harmless, but the real burden is to prove that at least one space supports the whole package: local theory, perturbation theory, profile decomposition, symmetry normalization, pressure control, and a notion of compactness compatible with the intended rigidity lever. A ranking memo can hide the fact that no candidate actually clears that bar.
    18	
    19	The kill condition is also weakly calibrated. "No candidate space supports a credible minimal-element package" is correct in spirit, but "credible" invites hand-waving. The branch should die unless one can name the exact extraction theorem, stability theorem, and compactness notion to be used, not just a favored space.
    20	
    21	## Step 2 - Fix one candidate rigidity lever up front
    22	
    23	This is where the chain becomes most speculative.
    24	
    25	- The proposed levers are placeholders, not mechanisms. "Tensor-sign law," "Lagrangian/topological invariant," and "pressure-Hessian feature" are categories, not usable objects.
    26	- The filter "reject anything Tao's averaged model plausibly preserves" is not a reliable research criterion. A lever can fail in the averaged model for irrelevant reasons, or survive averaging and still be exactly the right tool for real NS.
    27	- Requiring Tao-sensitivity before the extraction package is built biases the search toward novelty theater. It rewards mechanisms that sound NS-specific rather than mechanisms that can actually be applied to an almost-periodic critical element.
    28	
    29	There is also a sequencing problem. In most compactness-rigidity programs, the hypothetical critical element tells you what rigidity information is even geometrically available. Here the chain asks for the rigidity weapon before it knows the target's regularity, compactness modulus, or pressure information. That is backwards.
    30	
    31	The kill condition is too aggressive in one direction and too permissive in another. It is too aggressive because a promising route might only reveal the right rigidity quantity after the minimal object is formulated. It is too permissive because merely "naming" a Tao-sensitive lever is not progress unless one can state its sign, monotonicity, coercivity, or contradiction mechanism on the intended class of solutions.
    32	
    33	## Step 3 - Build the minimal-counterexample dossier
    34	
    35	This step hides the hardest analytic work inside the word "dossier."
    36	
    37	- Formulating a minimal blowup object in Navier-Stokes is not bookkeeping. It requires a serious extraction package, not just a template borrowed from dispersive PDE.
    38	- "State exactly what compactness or almost-periodicity statements are required" is really asking for the core theorem. If those statements are missing, the program is not partially built; it is blocked at the foundation.
    39	- Symmetry normalization is not trivial. Spatial translation and scaling are obvious, but Galilean issues, pressure normalization, and the chosen solution framework all affect what "minimal" even means.
    40	
    41	The dependency on Step 2 is also questionable. One can and probably should formulate the hypothetical critical object before overcommitting to a rigidity lever. Otherwise the chain risks reverse-engineering the object to fit the preferred lever.
    42	
    43	The kill condition again sounds precise but is softer than it looks. A "clean formulation" can be written on paper while still relying on unproved profile decomposition, unproved critical stability, or an incompatible solution class. The step should fail unless the object is definable with a clear dependency graph to known results and one sharply identified missing theorem.
    44	
    45	## Step 4 - Stress-test the rigidity route on the dossier
    46	
    47	This is the right stress test, but the step assumes too much by saying "run the promoted rigidity lever" as if a contradiction pathway is already visible.
    48	
    49	- In NS there is no standard virial, channel of energy, or finite-speed mechanism waiting to be plugged in once compactness appears.
    50	- Even if an almost-periodic critical element exists, it is far from obvious that the chosen lever is defined on that class, let alone strong enough to force triviality.
    51	- The pressure term is a recurring spoiler. Any rigidity mechanism that depends on second-order pressure structure can fail simply because the available compactness is too weak to pass that structure to the limit.
    52	
    53	The "first missing NS-specific lemma" criterion is good in spirit but under-specified. Many such lemmas are just the regularity problem in disguise. The chain should require a real complexity drop: the missing lemma should apply to a much narrower class than arbitrary finite-energy solutions and should exploit the compactness normalization in an essential way.
    54	
    55	The downgrade rule is also too binary. A lever can fail without collapsing to Tao-preserved structure. It can fail because the compactness class is too weak, because the quantity is not coercive, or because the limiting object lacks the regularity needed to state the argument. Those are different failure modes and should be separated.
    56	
    57	## Step 5 - Close with the narrowest earned claim
    58	
    59	This step has the right instinct but the wrong bar.
    60	
    61	- A "compactness-plus-rigidity roadmap" is too cheap an output after four steps. The chain can still exit with an elegant narrative that hides the absence of any executable theorem path.
    62	- The final claim should be forced into theorem-like form: assumptions, exact known inputs, exact missing lemma, and a statement of what would follow if that lemma were proved.
    63	- The obstruction option is valuable, but only if it names the exact failure point. "The route is still blocked" is not enough. It must say whether the block is extraction, stability, normalization, definability of the rigidity quantity, or failure of contradiction even under almost periodicity.
    64	
    65	The kill condition only guards against rhetorical blur across multiple phase spaces or levers. It does not guard against the more likely failure: smuggling in an unproved stability theorem or an unearned compactness statement while pretending the only remaining gap is the sexy NS-specific rigidity lemma.
    66	
    67	## Structural Weaknesses
    68	
    69	- The whole chain is structurally biased toward a predetermined conclusion: if local estimates stall, pivot to concentration-compactness plus rigidity. That is a familiar aesthetic move, not an argued reason that this is the best remaining path.
    70	- The chain's novelty claim is fragile. Without a concrete NS-only rigidity identity, this is mostly prior-art overlap with the standard critical-element playbook adapted to Navier-Stokes.

